SIMPLE: uneasy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Uneasy
<hw>Un*eas"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not easy;
difficult.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Things . . . so <qex>uneasy</qex> to be satisfactorily
understood.</q> <rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The road will be <qex>uneasy</qex> to find.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Restless; disturbed by pain, anxiety, or the like;
disquieted; perturbed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The soul, <qex>uneasy</qex> and confined from home,⟦br⟧
Rests and expatiates in a life to come.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not easy in manner; constrained; stiff; awkward; not
graceful; <as>as, an <ex>uneasy</ex> deportment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Occasioning want of ease; constraining; cramping;
disagreeable; unpleasing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>uneasy</xex>
station.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sour, untractable nature makes him <qex>uneasy</qex> to those
who approach him.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Uneath</ent>⟦br⟧
